    {
      "id": "P7Of9G",
      "text": "The **Bonding System** connects all submerged metallic components (thru-hulls, shafts, struts, etc.) to a common point, often connected to a sacrificial anode. Its primary function is to equalize electrical potential between dissimilar underwater metals to manage and mitigate **galvanic corrosion**.\n\nThe **Grounding System** (specifically the AC Safety Ground) is a safety circuit for the boat's 120V/240V AC system. Its purpose is to provide a low-resistance path for AC fault currents to trip a circuit breaker, preventing electric shock hazards. While the bonding system can contribute to a boat's **lightning protection** by providing a large surface area path to the water, the grounding system can sometimes **cause** **galvanic corrosion** if the shore power connection introduces stray DC currents, necessitating isolation devices.",
      "type": "markdown",
      "headline": "Bonding and Grounding Systems"
    },
