      "id": "tHNaGg",
      "text": "A sailboat's DC electrical system is typically split into two primary, isolated banks:\n\n*   **The House Bank:** A deep-cycle battery bank (usually 12V or 24V) designed to power all sustained onboard loads, including navigation electronics, refrigeration, lights, and pumps. It is built for deep discharges and long-term cycling.\n*   **The Engine/Starting Bank:** A high-cranking-amp battery dedicated exclusively to providing the necessary burst of power to crank the engine. It is kept separate and typically fully charged to guarantee reliable engine starting, regardless of the house bank's state of charge.\n\nThese banks are often managed by a **Battery Switch** and an **Automatic Charging Relay (ACR)** or **Battery Isolator**, which allows charging sources (like the alternator) to replenish both banks while ensuring they remain electrically separated during discharge.",
      "type": "markdown",
      "headline": "DC House and Engine Systems"
    },
    {
      "id": "vpqh0x",
      "text": "The **High-Output Marine Alternator** is a heavy-duty alternator driven by the engine, designed to generate significantly more amperage than a standard unit to rapidly replenish large 'House' battery banks. Its function is to convert mechanical engine power into electrical charging power. \n\nThis high output must be managed by a **Smart Regulator** (or external voltage regulator). The smart regulator's critical role is to employ multi-stage charging (Bulk, Absorption, Float) based on real-time battery voltage and temperature. This precise control maximizes charging efficiency and speed while protecting the batteries from overcharging and ensuring a full charge, which is vital for long battery life.",
      "type": "markdown",
      "headline": "DC Charging Sources"
    }
